alexander lee stanford dept of political science search search this site stanford university department of political science people phd admissions research honors track workshops job market candidates alexander lee navigation home people graduate program prospective students admitted students current students undergraduate program political science major political science minor summer research college workshops and events research contact home people students alexander lee alexander lee ph d candidate e mail amlee at stanford dot edu view cv biography alexander lee is a phd candidate in comparative politics with international relations and american politics as additional fields his research focuses on the politics of the developing world especially south asia and the historical factors governing the success or failure of political institutions his dissertation diversity and power caste in indian politics examines the effect of the economic and social changes during the colonial period on caste identity formation and the distribution of power among caste groups and traces the long term effect of these caste structures on the politics of post independence india particularly on regional and subregional variation in political development additional research areas include the long term consequences of colonialism and european expansion and the cause of political violence especially terrorism he has just returned from a year of fieldwork in india based in delhi and patna last modified monday february 13 2012 2 23pm secondary links stanford home school of humanities and science contact login stanford university department of political science encina hall west suite 100 stanford california 94305 6044 phone 650 723 1806 fax 650 723 1808
